    To get your website onto Google and = make it discoverable, you'll primarily need to focus on two key areas: h= osting and Search Engine Optimization (SEO).

    Here's a brea= kdown of the steps:

    1. Web Hosting:

        Choose a Hosting Provider: You need a service that stores your = website files (HTML, CSS, JS) and makes them accessible on the internet. Po= pular options include:

        • Shared Hosting: (e.g., Bluehost= , HostGator) Good for beginners and smaller sites.

        • VPS (V= irtual Private Server) Hosting: More control and resources than shared = hosting.

        • Cloud Hosting: (e.g., AWS, Google Cloud, Azu= re) Scalable and flexible.

        • Static Site Hosting: (e.g.= , Netlify, Vercel, GitHub Pages) Excellent for simple HTML/CSS/JS sites lik= e yours, often free or very low cost.

      • Upload Yo= ur Files: Once you have hosting, you'll upload your index.html, upper-body-anatomy-isolation.html, lower-body-anat= omy-isolation.html, and training-principles-advanced.html files (and any other assets like images if you add them later) to your h= osting provider's server. They usually provide tools like FTP or a web-base= d file manager for this.

      • Domain Name: You'll want a c= ustom domain name (e.g., musclescience.com). You can purchase = this from a domain registrar (like GoDaddy, Namecheap) and then link it to = your hosting.

    2. Search Engine Optimization (SEO):=

      • Google Search Console (formerly Webmaster Tools):= This is your most important tool for interacting with Google.

        • <= p>Verify Your Site: Add and verify your website in Google Search Con= sole.

        • Submit a Sitemap: Create an XML sitemap (a file= listing all the pages on your site) and submit it to Search Console. This = helps Google discover all your pages.

        • Monitor Performance= : Use Search Console to see how your site is performing in search resul= ts, identify crawl errors, and understand which queries users are using to = find your site.

      • On-Page SEO Basics:

          =

        • Keywords: While not as critical as they once were, using rele= vant keywords naturally in your content (e.g., "muscle growth," "training s= plits," "protein intake") helps Google understand what your pages are about= .

        • Meta Title & Description: Ensure each HTML page= has a descriptive <title> tag and a compelling &l= t;meta name=3D"description"> tag in the <head>= section. These appear in search results.

        • Header Tags (H1= , H2, H3): Use these to structure your content logically, as you've alr= eady done. This helps Google understand the hierarchy and main topics of yo= ur pages.

        • Image Alt Text: Add descriptive alt attributes to your images (e.g., <img src=3D"..." alt=3D"Upp= er Pec Muscle Anatomy">). This helps search engines understand im= age content and improves accessibility.

        • Internal Linking:= You've already done this well by linking between your pages. This help= s Google discover all your content and understand the relationships between= your pages.

        • Mobile-Friendliness: Your current code u= ses Tailwind CSS and a responsive viewport meta tag, which is great for mob= ile-friendliness =E2=80=93 a key ranking factor.

      • <= b>Off-Page SEO:

        • Backlinks: When other reputable we= bsites link to your site, it signals to Google that your content is valuabl= e and trustworthy. This is often the hardest part of SEO.

        • Social Media: While direct social media shares don't directly boost ra= nkings much, they can drive traffic to your site, which can indirectly help= with visibility.

    In summary:

    1. Host your website (e.g., on Netlify, GitHub = Pages, or a traditional web host).

    2. Register a domain name= and point it to your host.

    3. Set up Google Search Cons= ole and submit your sitemap.

    4. Continue to create high-= quality, informative content and ensure your on-page SEO is solid.

      <= /li>

    It takes time for Google to crawl and index new websites, so be= patient!

    2. Create a New Repository:

    Step 4: Tell Google About Your Website (Google Sear= ch Console)
